e-combining to text-embedded syntactic packaging -- tII Oral and written communication Section 4: Communication and discourse -- t13. Theory of mind and communication: Developmental perspectives -- t14. Socio-pragmatic skills underlying language development: Boundaries between typical and atypical development -- t15. Learning conversational skills and learning from conversation -- t16. Narrative Discourse: Developmental Perspectives -- t17. Narrative interventions for children with language disorders: A review of practices and findings -- t18. Helping language learning in inclusive classrooms -- tII Oral and written communication Section 5: Linguistic literacy -- t19. What is literacy? And what is a literate disability? -- t20. Promoting early literacy of children from low socioeconomic backgrounds in preschool and at home -- t21. Foundations for a universal model of learning to read -- t22. Acquisition of spelling: Normal and impaired/disordered populations -- t23 .The role of morphology in reading and writing -- t24. Reading comprehension: Individual differences, disorders, and underlying cognitive processes -- t25. Grammar for writing and grammar in writing -- tIII Environmental effects Section 6: Socio-economic status -- t26. How socioeconomic differences in early language environments shape children’s language development -- t27. Cognition and language in different socioeconomic and environmental settings -- t28. Language disorder versus language difference: The impact of socio-economic status -- tIII Environmental effects Section 7: Multilingualism -- t29. Input, context and early child bilingualism: Implications for clinical practice -- t30. SLI in bilingual development: How do we approach assessment? -- t31. Development of vocabulary knowledge and its relationship with reading comprehension among emergent bilingual children: An overview -- t32. Factors affecting second language acquisition: Successes and nonsuccesses -- tIV. Language